  "market_context": "EURUSD in bearish expansion on the daily timeframe. After a large bearish daily candle, the following day produced a retracement candle with a large upper wick rather than consolidation or opposing expansion, signaling continuation lower was anticipated.",
  "key_observation": "Because the daily candle showed a retracement (not consolidation or opposing expansion) with a large wick, the analyst used 0.5 of that wick as the premium boundary; price respecting it confirmed continuation lower.",
  "analysis_steps": [
    "Step 1: Identified that the prior daily candle was a bearish closure and the following candle was a retracement (not consolidation or opposing expansion), maintaining the bearish bias.",
    "Step 2: Applied 0.5 of the large upper wick as the premium reference, expecting price to respect this level and continue lower.",
    "Step 3: Dropped to the 1H chart on the new day to find intraday structure; noted the consolidation area on the left so did not trust it as an order block and instead used the range high as a POI for a sweep or SMT.",
    "Step 4: Observed price open and form a high that swept the level while respecting ~0.5 of the daily wick (allowing some tolerance above).",
    "Step 5: Confirmed a change in state of delivery at the sweep, paired with the PD array, validating short entry.",
    "Step 6: Anticipated continuation lower through the PD arrays and asked whether invalidation existed — price needed to hold below the wick midpoint."
  ],
  "outcome": "Price respected 0.5 of the daily wick, formed a CISD at the sweep, and continued lower through PD arrays as anticipated.",
  "lessons": "When a daily candle is a retracement (not consolidation/opposing expansion) with a large wick, use 0.5 of the wick as the premium boundary. Combine with intraday sweep + CISD at a POI to time continuation entries in the HTF direction.",
